5
00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:47.000
Thank you for the opportunity to be here today. I'm John Kensington, the chair of the External Reporting Board. I've been on the chair since last August, and I've been a board member by eight years prior to that. I'm joined by Wendy, our chief executive, Wendy Venter, along with Dr Amelia Sharman, our director of sustainability reporting and Dawn Bowden, our general manager corporate services.

6
00:02:47.000 --> 00:03:09.000
Now, the XRB sets financial reporting standards, assurance standards and climate reporting standards that provide consistent, internationally comparable information people can trust and use to make decisions. And those standards apply across the entire economy from large listed companies, public sector organizations through to charities and corporate societies and small owner operated businesses.

7
00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:24.000
It is important to note, we do not regulate or enforce those standards, and we do not decide who they apply to. So Parliament sets the legislative requirements and regulators such as the FMA or Charity Services are responsible for oversight and enforcement.

8
00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:34.000
But what we do underpins confidence in New Zealand's economy supports access to global capital, strengthens transparency and accountability across both the public and private sectors.

9
00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:42.000
So high quality standards are not an end in themselves. There are means to better government, risk management and capital allocation.

10
00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:52.000
Now, as the world becomes more complex and transactions become more complex, reporting becomes more complex. So it's proportionality really matters.

11
00:03:52.000 --> 00:04:06.000
And that's why in New Zealand we use the tiered system, so that the large entities can report the information they need to be able to meet international expectations, whereas smaller organizations report information more appropriate to their size.

12
00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:11.000
