00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:29.000
You know, our sense is yes.

195
00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:32.000
But some good information around that would be good.

196
00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:35.000
Yeah, I guess in a funny way, the counterfactual

197
00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:37.000
is probably important too.

198
00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:39.000
If you didn't have good quality standards,

199
00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:42.000
New Zealand's been lucky and we haven't had a financial crisis

200
00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:45.000
of the magnitude of any of some other countries.

201
00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:47.000
And I think that is probably down to the fact

202
00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:49.000
that there has been disciplines in place

203
00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:51.000
and required reporting in place,

204
00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:54.000
and that reporting has gone through boards

205
00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:56.000
and been considered and challenged.

206
00:22:56.000 --> 00:23:00.000
So, you know, the counterfactual is take away the accounting standards,

207
00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:03.000
let industry use whatever they like.

208
00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:05.000
It's a mad max vibration.

209
00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:09.000
Yeah, so I think what I'm saying is we need information

210
00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:12.000
around how the standards are, as Hamish was saying,

211
00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:14.000
being utilised and implanted.

212
00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:15.000
Yeah, no, absolutely.

213
00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:18.000
No, and it's essentially that point around the performance,

214
00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:20.000
how do you get impact?

215
00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:23.000
Actually, there is an element of what are the broader indicators.

216
00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:25.000
We might not have direct line of sight

217
00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:27.000
of exactly what is that standard.

218
00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:29.000
What can we do to collect that information?

219
00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:31.000
I don't understand the point.

220
00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:33.000
Okay, Dr Hamish.

221
00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:35.000
And probably following on from that,

222
00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:38.000
you operate in a rich ecosystem

223
00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:41.000
with many different players

224
00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:45.000
from the FMA, the Auditor General's Office,

225
00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:49.000
Treasury, and will probably produce guidance.

226
00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:52.000
How do you ensure that are you working together

227
00:23:52.000 --> 00:23:57.000
in this no duplication of effort between different organizations?

228
00:23:57.000 --> 00:23:59.000
Yeah, look, for example, probably the best example

229
00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:01.000
that is with the FMA.

230
00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:02.000
We have an MOU of them.

231
00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:04.000
We probably put it in place about three years ago.

232
00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:07.000
We talked to them about, hey, please don't,

233
00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:09.000
you try and set standards.

234
00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:10.000
If you want a standard to be set

235
00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:11.000
because you think something's not there,

236
00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:13.000
come and talk to us and we can do that,

237
00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:15.000
and we won't cross across into regulation.

238
00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:18.000
And I guess we regularly meet

239
00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:20.000
with the players in the ecosystem

240
00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:22.000
to make sure we are doing,

241
00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:25.000
effectively staying in our lane, I suppose.

242
00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:27.000
Yeah.

243
00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:32.000
And I suppose that's kind of internal in New Zealand.

244
00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:35.000
Talked about being a standard

245
00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:38.000
to take care of a regulation taker.

246
00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:41.000
Is there a stage where, actually,

247
00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:44.000
it's ridiculous New Zealand has its own entity

248
00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:46.000
to do this rather than actually just

249
00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:49.000
fully taking standards from

250
00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:51.000
Australia, the UK,

251
00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:53.000
other jurisdictions?

252
00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:54.000
Yeah.

253
00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:58.000
New Zealand has a fairly unique TED system,

254
00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:00.000
which ensures the large entities.

255
00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:02.000
So banks insurers from Terra,

256
00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:04.000
they're reporting all the information there,

257
00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:06.000
compatriots overseas.

258
00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:09.000
We've also got at the bottom end of that TED system,

259
00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:12.000
reporting requirements specifically designed

260
00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:13.000
for New Zealand entities.

261
00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:16.000
So the risk of going to a jurisdiction

262
00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:19.000
and relying completely on another jurisdiction is

263
00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:22.000
you'd be stuck with their tearing,

264
00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:25.000
which may not really consider some of those

265
00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:27.000
bottom-end entities that New Zealand has,

266
00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:29.000
or size-wise.

267
00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:30.000
Yeah.

268
00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:32.000
Great. Looks like that's it.

269
00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:34.000
Thank you so much for your time,

270
00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:36.000
and thanks for answering questions.

271
00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:39.000
And you might have more questions later on from us.

272
00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:40.000
Thank you.

273
00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:41.000
Thank you.

274
00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:42.000
Thanks for the opportunity.

275
